## DON'T

```typescript
// Bad variable names
const u = getUser(); // VIOLATION: too short
const user_data = {}; // VIOLATION: snake_case
const UserCount = 10; // VIOLATION: PascalCase for variable
const isauth = true; // VIOLATION: missing camelCase

// Bad function names
function get() {} // VIOLATION: not descriptive
function getUserDataById() {} // VIOLATION: redundant "Data"
function handle_user_submit() {} // VIOLATION: snake_case

// Bad class names
class userService {} // VIOLATION: camelCase
class USER_SERVICE {} // VIOLATION: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE

// Bad constants
const apiBaseUrl = 'https://api.example.com'; // VIOLATION: should be UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
const maxRetries = 3; // VIOLATION: should be UPPER_SNAKE_CASE

// Bad file names
// UsersController.ts (should be users.controller.ts)
// user-service.ts (OK but prefer user.service.ts)
// useAuth.tsx (should be use-auth.ts or useAuth.ts)
```

```typescript
// Bad boolean naming
const authenticated = true; // VIOLATION: should be isAuthenticated
const permission = false; // VIOLATION: should be hasPermission

// Bad array naming
const user = []; // VIOLATION: should be users
const tripList = []; // VIOLATION: should be trips

// Bad event handler naming
const submit = () => {}; // VIOLATION: should be handleSubmit or onSubmit
```

## Special Cases

### Private Members
- Prefix private class members with underscore: `_privateMethod()`.
- Use TypeScript `private` keyword, underscore is optional but recommended.

### Generic Types
- Use single uppercase letters: `T`, `K`, `V`, `U`.
- Use descriptive names for complex generics: `TEntity`, `TResponse`.

### Abbreviations
- Avoid abbreviations unless widely understood (e.g., `id`, `url`, `api`).
- Use full words for clarity: `userId` not `usrId`, `userName` not `usrNm`.

### Boolean Prefixes
- `is`: state or condition (`isActive`, `isLoading`).
- `has`: possession or existence (`hasPermission`, `hasError`).
- `should`: recommendation or requirement (`shouldRetry`, `shouldValidate`).
- `can`: capability (`canEdit`, `canDelete`).
- `will`: future action (`willSubmit`, `willNavigate`).

## Exceptions

- Test files may use descriptive names even if longer than usual.
- Configuration objects may use `camelCase` even if they represent constants.
- Third-party library adapters may follow library conventions.
